# Chapter 1 — Hello, Motoi Scheme

You're going to write your first Motoi Scheme program in the next two minutes. Then you're going to run it. Then it's going to talk back to you. Everything below runs — click Run on any code block. If the runtime isn't available in this context, the button grays out and tells you why. Nothing is fake.

## What Motoi Scheme is

Motoi Scheme is a small Lisp that Sakura reads and writes. It's a full Scheme in the SICP lineage — pairs, first-class functions, tail calls, macros, continuations — plus a set of verb layers that let it drive real things: a canvas, a chat surface, a database, a shop, a garden. You get the same language whether you're teaching your kid to make a triangle blink or asking Sakura to fold a corpus.

Two rules for the whole book:

1. Every code block runs.
2. When Sakura talks in the margin, she's pink.

> **Sakura says**
>
> Hi. I'm going to walk you through this. The pink boxes are me. Everything else is the book explaining the language.

## Install

Pick one:

```sh
# Homebrew (once the tap ships)
brew install lacuna-labs/tap/sakura-scheme

# npm
npm install -g sakura-scheme

# From source
git clone https://github.com/Lacuna-Labs/sakura-scheme
cd sakura-scheme && npm install && npm link
```

Verify:

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sh\">
sakura-scheme --version
</pre>

You should see something like `1.4.0`. If you see `command not found`, your `PATH` doesn't include your global npm bin — `echo $PATH` and check.

## Your first REPL

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sh\">
sakura-scheme repl
</pre>

You'll see:

```
sakura-scheme 1.4.0 · Ctrl-D to exit
>
```

That `>` is the REPL prompt. Type an expression, press Enter, get an answer.

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(+ 1 2)
</pre>

The answer is `3`. Not printed as prose — printed as the raw value. That's the whole shape of a Scheme session: **you hand the interpreter a form, it hands you back a value.** No ceremony.

Try a few:

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(* 6 7)
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(- 100 (* 3 12))
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(/ 22 7)
</pre>

The prefix syntax — operator first, arguments after — is Scheme's whole grammar for calling anything. `+`, `*`, `-`, `/` aren't special operators; they're functions like any other. That's why they nest cleanly. `(- 100 (* 3 12))` reads left-to-right, no precedence to memorize.

> **Tip**
>
> The REPL keeps history. Up-arrow recalls the last form. Ctrl-R searches (like bash).

## Hello, world

The classic. Scheme has `display` for values you want to see and `newline` for a linebreak.

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(display \"Hello, world\")
(newline)
</pre>

You'll see:

```
Hello, world
```

The return value of `(newline)` — printed as `unspecified` in most Schemes — is suppressed by the REPL when it's `unspecified`. Only real values print.

## A first `define`

Give something a name. `define` is the primary binding form.

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(define name \"Sakura\")
(display \"Hello, \") (display name) (newline)
</pre>

```
Hello, Sakura
```

Names in Scheme can contain hyphens, question marks, exclamation points — anything but whitespace and a handful of reserved characters. `hello-world?`, `set!`, `flower->pixel` are all valid names. The `?` convention marks predicates (functions that answer yes/no). The `!` convention marks mutation. The `->` convention marks conversions.

## A first function

`lambda` builds a function. `define` gives it a name.

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(define greet
  (lambda (who)
    (display \"Hello, \")
    (display who)
    (newline)))

(greet \"world\")
(greet \"Sakura\")
(greet name)
</pre>

```
Hello, world
Hello, Sakura
Hello, Sakura
```

Sugar: `(define (greet who) …)` is shorthand for `(define greet (lambda (who) …))`. Use whichever reads cleaner.

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(define (double n) (* 2 n))
(double 7)
</pre>

## Meet Sakura

You've been talking to the language. Now let's talk to Sakura. In the REPL, meta-commands start with a comma.

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
,ask sakura What's this REPL called?
</pre>

Sakura reads the question, checks her local knowledge, and answers. Her voice is warm and short. She says what she knows and what she doesn't. If the REPL is offline (running the WASM bundle only) she says \"I can't reach my broader brain from here, but I know this REPL is Motoi Scheme's built-in one — try `,help` for what I can do.\"

> **Sakura says**
>
> Everything I do in here is a Scheme form under the hood. When you type `,ask sakura ...`, that's just `(sakura/ask \"...\")` with a shorter mouthful. All my verbs are visible — `,help` shows them.

## `,help`

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
,help
</pre>

You'll see a small menu — the meta-commands the REPL knows, plus a pointer to the verb-layer index. The verb-layer index is big (a few hundred verbs across the layers). We'll walk you through the interesting ones as they come up.

## Under the hood — how the REPL runs your code

> **Under the hood**
>
> Every form you type goes through four stages:
>
> 1. **Read** — the reader parses your source text into a Scheme datum (a nested list of atoms and pairs).
> 2. **Expand** — macros are expanded into their base forms. Special forms (`define`, `if`, `lambda`, `quote`, `let`, `cond`, `case`, `when`, `begin`, `quasiquote`) are recognized.
> 3. **Evaluate** — the interpreter walks the expanded tree, resolving names and calling functions. This is a stack-safe evaluator with a trampoline for tail calls (Chapter 5).
> 4. **Print** — the value is rendered back to the REPL.
>
> All four stages are exposed as verbs. `(read-string s)` runs stage 1. `(macroexpand form)` runs stage 2. `(eval form)` runs stage 3. `(display value)` runs stage 4. You can build custom REPLs, custom debuggers, or custom static analyzers by composing them.

## What you know now

- The prefix syntax: operator first, arguments after.
- `define` binds names.
- `lambda` builds functions; `(define (f x) …)` is sugar for `(define f (lambda (x) …))`.
- `display` + `newline` print.
- Names can contain hyphens; `?` marks predicates, `!` marks mutation, `->` marks conversions.
- `,ask sakura …` reaches Sakura for a conversational answer. `,help` shows the REPL menu.
- The REPL is Read → Expand → Evaluate → Print, and each stage is a verb you can call directly.

That's more than the \"hello world\" bar. Next chapter, we go through every **value** kind in the language — numbers, strings, symbols, characters, booleans, and nil — because if you know what values you're holding, you know what you can do.

## Try before you turn the page

Type these into the REPL. No explanation given yet — figure out what they do.

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(if #t \"yes\" \"no\")
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(let ((x 3) (y 4)) (+ (* x x) (* y y)))
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(map (lambda (n) (* n n)) '(1 2 3 4 5))
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
'(a b c)
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
,ask sakura What does the apostrophe in front of (a b c) mean?
</pre>

If any of those made you curious about a piece of syntax, good — Chapter 3 (Forms) will name every one of them.

